Cars4U Project

Context¶

Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholes in the Used car market as pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years (specifically between 2018-19). Unlike New Cars where pricing and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer / except for dealership level discounts, used cars have huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Therefore, it is very important for Cars4U as a start-up to be able to determine what its future supply and pricing will be like in order to manage its future growth and keep a foothole in ever growing Used car market.

Objective¶

Analyze the data and come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing.

Key Questions¶

  1. What car brands are the top selling in the Indian Market?
  2. Is the market dominated by Economical or luxury cars?
  3. What is the Median price for a new car?
  4. What is the Median price for a pre-owned car?
  5. What transmission type is preferred the most?
  6. What Fuel_Type is preferred the most?
  7. What is the market share for Pre-owned cars in general?

In [15]:
def mileage_to_num(mileage_val):
    """
    This function takes in a string representing in Mileage in km/kg & kmpl
    and converts it to a number. For Example, 26.6 km/kg to 26.6
    or 19.67 kmpl to 19.67
    """
    if isinstance(mileage_val, str):  # checks if `mileage_val` is a string
        return float(mileage_val.replace("km/kg", "").replace("kmpl", ""))
    else:
        return np.nan


for colname in mileage_cols:
    df2[colname] = df2[colname].apply(mileage_to_num)

Base Model - to help understand performance progress in our final model

Data must not include missing values, long texts must be processed, textual content must be converted to numeric before it can be one-hot encoded and further built for a Base Model which is very useful in the end for comparison reasons

Reusable Method for Performance checking of the model

In [32]:
# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))


# function to compute MAPE
def mape_score(targets, predictions):
    return np.mean(np.abs(targets - predictions) / targets) * 100


# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_performance_regression(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check regression model performance

    model: regressor
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(target, pred))  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE
    mape = mape_score(target, pred)  # to compute MAPE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2,
            "MAPE": mape,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Reusable Method for Histplot and boxplot

In [42]:
def hist_box(data, feature, figsize=(10, 5), kde=True, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and Histogram combined within the same graph page
    in order to make comparison and analysis more efficient

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of the figures (default (10,5))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (values set by user during usage - Boolean)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)"""
    # f2 holds are graph withax_box2 and ax_hist2 params
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of subplot grid=2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )

    # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet")

    if bins:
        sns.histplot(
            data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
        )
    else:
        sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2)  # For histogram

    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram

    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

Reusable Method for creating Barplots

In [43]:
def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

Reusable Method for Calculating A five-number summary values - printing most important ones

In [44]:
def five_number_summary(data, column_name):
    """
    column_name: name of the column that should be searched and stats described for
    """
    # To get the 25%quantile
    _25p = data[column_name].quantile(0.25)
    # To get the median
    _median = data[column_name].median()
    # To get the mean
    _mean = data[column_name].mean()
    # To get the 75%Quantile
    _75p = data[column_name].quantile(0.75)
    # To get the Standard Deviation
    std = data[column_name].std()
    print(
        "25%",
        _25p,
        "\n" "Mean-Green",
        _mean,
        "\n" "Median-Boxplot",
        _median,
        "\n" "75%",
        _75p,
        "\n",
        "StandarD",
        std,
        "\n",
    )

Analyzing Numeric Columns: Power¶

The maximum power of the engine in bhp

While hp does not take into account frictional losses in power from an engine, brake horsepower does — meaning hp is always higher than bhp. The difference between the two is small on a 1:1 basis. 1hp is the equivalent to just under 0.99bhp, though scaled up you'll notice differences

The average for crossovers is 200 hp, midsize autos put out 170 hp, while small SUVs are generally capable of 240 hp

Summary of EDA¶

Data Description:

  • The target variable (Price) is of float type.
  • Columns like Name, Location, Transmission, Fuel_Type,Owner_Type are of object type.
  • All other columns are numeric in nature.
  • There are no duplicate values in the data.
  • There are a lot of missing values in the data.

Data Cleaning:

  • The S.Nodropped as it was just a row ID which Pandas already provided.
  • The Names column were too long therefore were processed to shorten to Brand names in order to make it into a suitable format for Analysis and Modeling.
  • The Mileage, Engine, Power were converted into numeric columns.
  • The missing values in the data are treated as follows:
    • Missing values in the target variable Price were dropped.
    • Missing values in Power were imputed with their mean.
    • Missing values in Seats were imputed with their mean.
    • Missing values in Engine were imputed with their mean.
    • Missing values in Mileage were imputed with their mean.

Observations from EDA:

  • Year: Most the Manufacturing year of the car falls between 2011 and 2016 and contained left skewedness
  • Kilometers_Driven: Median Kilometers_Driven by previous user is 53000 where the range of km on pre-owned cars is between 34000 to 75000 KMs. There're lots of outliers here
  • Mileage: The distribution is skewed on both tail ends, the median kmpl is 18.15.
  • Engine: The distribution is heavily right-skewed, Given, The fact that the lower the cc of the car, the better the mileage obtained, cars with up to 1000 cc give the best mileage. In our case 25% of the Cars are below 1198 CC.
  • Power: Given that 250 horsepower in a very small car or about 400 horsepower in an exceptionally large vehicle, 75% of our Power data falls below 138bhp indicating that most of our vehicles are small/sedan type cars, which is true since Maruti, Honda, Hyundais hold 48.5% of Indian Car Market.
  • Seats: Average seating count for our vehicles is at 5, which is expected and proves that most of the vehicles in our data set are light vehicles (.i.e. Sedans).
  • New_Price: The distribution is heavily right-skewed with a median value of a car at 11.3K, 75% of the vehicles are under 22K
  • Price: The distribution is heavily right-skewed with Median price is at 7k which is just a little under the price tag of less than 25% of the vehicles are found in New_Price Column
  • Name: Maruti, Hyundai followed by Honda are the leading car brands holding about 49% of the Indian Market shares
  • Location: Delhi and Coimbatore has the highest cost for Owner_Type third type of cars around 40K
  • Fuel_Type: Diesel Vehicles holds more than half of the market share at 53%.
  • Transmission: Manual Transmission type of cars are preffered over Automatic at 71%, this could be due to better mileage on Manual than Automatic.
  • Owner_Type: Large majority of the vehicles are first hand at 82%
  • Below columns were highly correlated but not removed since our objective here was to simply predict not infer at this point.
    • Engine & Power - Highly correlated
    • Power & Engine - Highly correlated
    • New_Price & Power - Highly correlated
    • New_Price & Engine - Highly correlated

Model performance check

  • We will be using metric functions defined in sklearn for RMSE, MAE, and $R^2$.

  • We will define functions to calculate adjusted $R^2$ and MAPE.

    • The mean absolute percentage error (MAPE) measures the accuracy of predictions as a percentage, and can be calculated as the average absolute percent error for each predicted value minus actual values divided by actual values. It works best if there are no extreme values in the data and none of the actual values are 0.

  • We will create a function that will print out all the above metrics in one go.

Observations

  • The train and test $R^2$ are 0.93 and 0.94, indicating that the model explains 93% and 94% of the total variation in the train and test sets respectively. Also, both scores are comparable.

  • RMSE values on the train and test sets are also comparable, RMSE value in training 0.18 and test 0.17

which indicates to a better fit since RMSE has dropped in Test Data.

  • This shows that the model is not overfitting.

  • MAE indicates that our current model is able to predict price of used cars within a mean error of 0.12 on the test set.

  • MAPE of 7.42 on the test data means that we are able to predict ~8% of the price of used cars,

this also means that forecasted value and the actual value is 7.42% which was at 7.88 in Training Set.

  • The overall performance is much better than the model we built in the previous session.

Conclusions & Recommendation that will help business¶

  • We have been able to build a predictive model that can be used by the business to predict the price of used cars with an $R^2$ of 0.935 on the training set and 0.946 on the Test data set
  • Business can use this model to predict the price of used cars within a mean error of 0.12 on the test set.
  • We improved our linear regression model performance by applying non-linear transformations to some of the attributes.
    • RMSE in base model is at 5.31 for Training and 6.17 for Test, where as after Variable Transformation it has gone down to 0.18 in Train and 0.17 in Test.
    • Mean Absolute Error has also gone down to 0.13 Train/ 0.12 Test in our current latest model from 2.86 Train / 2.78 from Base Model
    • Final model's $R^2$ has increased by 27% in Test model to being 94%, meaning that it explain 27% more of the Total Variation, where in base model it was just at 67%
    • Adjusted $R^2$ score in Test and Train has also gone up to little over 20% as well.

Given below market conditions:¶

  • Maruti, Hyundai and Honda accounts for 49% of the Indian Car Market's share, Meaning market is Dominated mainly by economical cars which are mainly of Diesel Fuel_Type.
  • The Median price of New car is at 11.3K where as pre-owned cars are at 6k and Manual Transmission is most preferred amongst drivers
  • Second Owner_Type vehicles accounts for 16.15% of the market share where as First hand type of cars accounts for 82%.
  • Delhi and Comibatore Sales on Thirda hand vehicles can top to 40K median price point

This could mean that:¶

  • There's a gap in the market due to the limit of inventory on used cars, which might explain the increase value for third hand cars in Delhi and Coimbatore at 40K while first, second hand cars are just under 20K

Business can look into:¶

  1. Closing this gap by building a smart and diverse inventory which consists of economical cars that are fueled by petrol, diesle and electricity
  2. While proviiding future potential buyers more options to choose from, the cars4u can make this options easier to choose from by running smart ad campaigns on each vehicles advnatage on mileage, comfort, reliability etc...
  3. Delhi and Coimbatore should be our focus markets
  4. Using our model Cars4U can better predict based on current data, and even much more going forward as more sales will lead to more data to be analyzed and predit price for pre-owned vehicles.
